data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0e06245ec6e6177f0069a8c68e4a1481958a77783bdad61e9f","logprobs":[],"output_index":6,"sequence_number":381,"text":"Kubernetes (“K8s”) is an open-source system for orchestrating (deploying, scaling, and managing) containerized applications. Its history is closely tied to Google’s long-running experience running containers at massive scale.\n\n- **Google roots (pre-2014):** Kubernetes was inspired by Google’s internal cluster-management systems—especially **Borg** (and lessons from **Omega**)—which managed large fleets of applications across Google’s infrastructure.\n\n- **Open-sourcing (2014):** Google released Kubernetes as an open-source project in **2014**, with engineers including Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie among its early creators. The name “Kubernetes” comes from Greek for “helmsman” (a ship’s pilot).\n\n- **Stewardship and standardization (2015):** In **2015**, Google partnered with other companies to found the **Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF)**, and Kubernetes became its flagship project, signaling vendor-neutral governance and accelerating broad industry adoption.\n\n- **Early maturation (2015–2017):** Kubernetes rapidly gained core features (e.g., Deployments, Services, scheduling, controllers, and extensibility) and an ecosystem of networking, storage, and monitoring integrations. This period also saw the rise of “cloud native” tooling around it.\n\n- **Becoming the industry default (2018–present):** Kubernetes became the dominant container-orchestration standard, supported across all major clouds and widely adopted on-prem. The project continued to expand via community-driven enhancements (e.g., CRDs/operators, improved scalability, security controls, and richer ecosystem interoperability).\n\nIf you tell me whether you want a **high-level business-oriented** history or a **more technical timeline** (versions/features), I can tailor the summary."}

